node.text: We had a blast in Jamaica and we can’t wait to do it again. As promised, I uploaded a full review of the resort we stayed in, and I just dropped an entire vlog on YouTube of our stay in Jamaica. Head to my website at thatnursecooks.com to check it out!!! Link in bio!!

So I got up this morning to get the kids ready and realized I forgot to buy milk last night 😱 Then I remembered the instant porridges that the lovely team at @gracefoods gave to me and I thought well they can eat this! It was their first time trying it and they loved it! You know I always make porridge for them so if they liked this, then it must be really good! Definitely adding this to my list of quick breakfasts for those school mornings when I’m short on time! .

node.text: It was extremely hard for me to find work when I graduated nursing school. It took me 6 months of prayer and non stop pounding the pavement for someone to give me an opportunity and even then it was only part time work. I humbly accepted the job because at that point, I was just grateful to be employed. The first thing I did was save money to buy a plane ticket to go see my grandmother in Jamaica. I hadn’t seen her in a decade. We spent 4 days together. Just she and I. My granny made sure I had cooked food every single day. She dazzled me with stories of her upbringing and I filled in some of the gaps from my childhood that she may have missed out on due to the fact that she lived abroad. She told me about how hard she had it living in the countryside and how she left my mother with her grandmother while she went to look for work in Montego Bay. Our mornings consisted of gospel radio, two slices of Giant Hard Dough bread and butter, and a cup of tea as we quietly enjoyed each other’s presence. We took a taxi cab to the market for fresh vegetables, herbs and spices, and she warned me not to drink all of the fresh coconut juice because it was guaranteed to give me a full bladder. On our way home we made sure to visit her neighbor who saved a nice pear for her, and when we returned home, we sat out on the veranda with a nice, cold glass of limeade as the sun went down, and the sky resembled a blanket of cotton candy. Some of my aunts even stopped by to see me, bearing gifts of coconut drops, grater cake, gizzada, and a freshly baked sweet potato pudding to bring home with me. The night before I was due to return home to New York, with the lights dimmed, she sat between my legs as I braided her hair in four. She said, “You know something? You have an old soul.”

node.text:
Caribbean Charcuterie? 😂 Cheese & Crackers just won’t get the job done for me, so make a board like this and bring your appetite, and have it ready at your next gathering!! (safely of course 😏) I’ve got:
-Jerk Chicken
-Festival
-Roast Corn
-Fried Plantain
-Watermelon Chow (my version: mint & a little balsamic vinaigrette drizzle)
-Grilled Pineapples
-Pear
-Lemon & Lime wedges to clean your hands
.
.
👉🏾Where are you starting on this board? 
.
.
.
.

A greedy girl’s charcuterie board will never have cheese & crackers on it 😂 I have to have the full hundred! Oven Jerk Chicken, Festival, Roast Corn, Fried Plantain, Grilled Pineapple, a Watermelon Chow, Pear, and a lemon & lime wedge to clean your hands when you’re done! Who wants some? Happy Sunday yall 😎
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
How do you make your rice? This is how I make my rice nice & shelly! No aluminum foil, definitely no plastic wrap/bag needed, and I’ve never owned a rice cooker 🤣 I don’t measure ingredients, over time, I’ve learned to rely on my judgment......and please tell me y’all are not out here cooking rice straight from the bag & not washing it first 😷😷. It’s the equivalent of not washing your meat if you ask me! New video now up on my 🎥YouTube channel: thatnursecancook with detailed step by step instructions!!! (Access via my website, link is in my bio)
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
I don’t use grocery delivery option very often because I’m so particular about how I shop for my groceries. Life has been life-ing lately so I got my groceries delivered. I needed to make a quick dinner so beef & broccoli it was! I ordered beef chuck steak. I wanted the small, flat cut, boneless ones, but the shopper picked this large, bone in steak. I made it work though! I simply cut them into bite sized pieces, chopped my veggies, and got busy. Dinner was ready in 30 minutes. The recipe is in my ebook “Dinner in 30” available for immediate download at shopthatnursecancook.com (link in bio)
.
.
.
.
.
.
